\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs16\super $}{ Defining Multiple Labels}}}{\b\f27 Defining Multiple Labels
\par }{\f1\fs18 
\par Label.dll takes a new approach to configuring multiple instances. Traditionally a module that supported multiple instances had to use *Config-style configuration where all the settings for each instance had to fit on a single line (like shortcuts.dll). Bu
t
 labels have too many settings to put on a single line so that approach was out of the question. Instead, each label is given a unique name and the settings for the label all begin with that name. For example, if there is a label named "MyLabel" then the 
settings for that label might look like:
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\keep\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18 MyLabelText "Hello, world!"
\par MyLabelImage mylabel.bmp
\par MyLabelHeight 24
\par MyLabelWidth 96
\par MyLabelX 64
\par MyLabelY 64
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18 
\par Simultaneously you can have another label named "MyOtherLabel":
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\keep\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18 MyOtherLabelText "Click Here!"
\par MyOtherLabelOnLeftClick !alert "Hello, world!"
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18 
\par You can have any number of labels so long as each one has a different name. Also be careful that your label names do not conflict with any other modules you have loaded. For instance, if chronos.dll is loaded then do
 not have a label named Chronos or else the settings will conflict and one module will not work correctly. In fact, I recommend that you put "Label" somewhere in the name to keep things straight, but label.dll places no restrictions on the names you can c
hoose except that they can only contains letters and numbers (no symbols or spaces).
\par 
\par By default, label.dll runs in a single-instance mode with only one label (named "Label") defined. To use multiple labels you need to use the following command:
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 Labels}{\f1\fs18  }{\i\f1\fs18 name-list}{\f1\fs18 
\par Gives the names of the labels you wish to define. All names must be unique and can only contains letters and numbers (no symbols or spaces). Separate names with commas and do not use quotes. If no value is provided then a single label named "Label" 
is created by default.
\par 
\par \page }{\cs16\b\f27\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs16\super #}{ BangCommands}}${\footnote \pard\plain 
\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs16\super $}{ Bang Commands}}K{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs16\super K}{
 !LabelAlwaysOnTop;!LabelHide;!LabelPinToDesktop;!LabelShow;!LabelSetText;!LabelToggleAlwaysOnTop;!LabelToggle}}}{\b\f27 Bang Commands
\par }{\f1\fs18 
\par Bang commands allow you to manipulate labels at run-time through scripts or other modules. Bang commands work the same way for multiple labels as settings. Just replace the name "Label" with the name of the label (for instance, "!MyLabelSetText").
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelAlwaysOnTop}{\f1\fs18 
\par Makes the label always on top, that is, it remains above all application windows.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelHide}{\f1\fs18 
\par Hides the label, making it invisible.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelPinToDesktop}{\f1\fs18 
\par Pins the label to the desktop so that it remains below all application windows. This is the default state and is the opposite of always on top.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelSetText}{\f1\fs18  }{\i\f1\fs18 text}{\f1\fs18 
\par Sets the text displayed in the label. If the }{\i\f1\fs18 text}{\f1\fs18  parameter is not there then the label will be blank.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelShow}{\f1\fs18 
\par Shows the label, making it visible.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelToggleAlwaysOnTop}{\f1\fs18 
\par Switches the label back and forth between the always on top and pinned to desktop states.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18 !LabelToggle}{\f1\fs18 
\par Switches the label back and forth between the visible and invisible states.
\par 
